<h1> Fake Front Door </h1>

  <div class="row">
    <div class="col-md-12">
    <h2>Overview:</h2>
     <p>The Fake Door experiment is the establishment of a facade that has nothing functional behind the scenes.
       If you’ve already got a customer base, using the fake door test is a fantastic way to gauge whether they’ll be interested
      in a new product or feature. A customer will see the door, interact with it and be told that there is nothing behind it. It
      is a great way to test out an idea, gain data on how your idea/product/site is being received.</p>


      </div>
  </div>

<br></br>

<div class="row">
  <div class="col-md-12">
  <h2>Why Run It?</h2>
   <p>When a new idea will require a lot of technical and business expertise and the team would like to learn more
      about their customer first. The customer segment provides an opportunity to identify what is priority for the
       group and what is considered a nice to have. The identification of the customer segment is one of the areas of
       the value proposition work.</p>
    <p>You can quickly see whether customers will engage with a new feature by launching just the first part of it.
       When developing a new feature that doesn't exist, it is hard to understand whether users will want it, because
        sometimes they don't know they want/need it!</p>

    </div>
